data.text: View Image Gallery Amazon Customer 4.0 out of 5 stars Great Inexpensive Entry Level Mic Reviewed in the United States on February 6, 2015 Great mic to step up in quality from a cheapo headset mic. Even though this is an entry level mic, it is a great value for the price. If you are looking to start a podcast this is the perfect mic without breaking the bank.Unfortunately there is a big time delay when wanting to monitor the mic with headphones. If you need to monitor yourself, buy a mic that plugs straight into the mic jack and not the USB port. I took off one star for this.Personally I don't need a monitor myself when recording so this mic fits my needs well. I thought I'd mention it though.UPDATE: I built out a little nook in my closet with some acoustic foam. This mic records even more great now!!! This is a fantastic mic to get in to recording voice or youtube videos. Please try again later.Wayfinder5.0 out of 5 stars The only recording mike you'll need Reviewed in the United States on December 3, 2014Verified Purchase At first I was going to give this mike 4 stars because I'm a perfectionist and I've seen better studio mikes. But those studio mikes were expensive; this one is under $50. Therefore, 5 stars. Here's why:PROS:* Good quality recording with variable settings on the mike itself* Very easy to install. No driver software-- just plug it in and it works* Responsive cyan LED to help indicate power / recording level* Excellent size. When set on a table it's at just about the perfect height for recording* Surprisingly good sound quality, especially for a mike this light-weight and low-priced* Neat little table tripod stand, easy to set up and use* Comes with generous-length cableCONS:None really. Terrific little mike. These are more "be aware of these things when recording":* This is (as advertised) a studio mike. It is really, really, really sensitive and will pick up all sounds in the room-- including computer fans and a small 10" room fan I had set on low about 6 feet away. Such noise of course can be easily overcome in post-processing using a program such as Audacity (available free on the Net) or other music processing software.* That said, it has a "bass switch" that provides reduction of background noise by reducing mike sensitivity for some sound levels.* That said... the bass switch also alters the overall quality of recording sound. This can also be adjusted via post-processing.* THAT said... it's best to record in an enclosed room using a tablet or laptop with as little fan sound as possible, because this WILL pick up all sound in the room. It's meant to do so to provide distortion-free recording.For best recording I use this with my Windows tablet (zero fan noise, easy portability and setup). The result is a very effective "recording studio" which does a good job for not a lotta cash. Quality Windows tablets today can be purchased for around $200. So that along with this mike and free downloaded software provides a good recording environment that will suit the needs of many users. And of course it functions perfectly as a high-quality computer mike for Skype or other chat purposes.WHAT TO EXPECT:A good-quality voice and instrument recording mike. Solo voice/guitar? Yes. Computer voice mike? Yes but it will pick up background noise. Group mike? Yes, it's a studio mike; it picks up sound well.WHAT NOT TO EXPECT:Don't expect $300 + $20 wind screen sound recording from this. It has very good sound recording, but there are better mikes on the market if your budget allows. However if you're on a limited budget and want GOOD results and would like a USB mike that plugs right into your computer, I don't believe this can be beat. I've purchased several microphones and this has as good a quality sound recording as any mike I have purchased.This isn't a "band" mike. This is for use in "studio conditions" (ie, in a closed environment without background noise) directly plugged into your computer's USB port. Used as an outdoor mike at a concert or such... well I haven't tried that yet. Typically studio mikes are not good for such. Used in live performance: no. The background noise pickup and feedback potential would be immense.SOLO STUDIO RECORDING:Because it does pick up external noise you can play it with an acoustic instrument without miking the instrument separately; it will pick up about the same quality and positioning as the human ear. Interestingly this mike seems to work better from 12 inches than the standard 2 to 4 inches that most recording mikes prefer. I got excellent results when recording at 12". At 2" from the mouth the sound is still excellent but one gets the feeling of "really not necessary and is actually too much". 12" or even further seems perfect, which is great news for solo acoustic guitar performers.This mike would work equally well running an electric guitar through an amp and setting the amp to the side. The mike has such faithful reproduction of sound it should lose little or nothing in the distance translation.In short, a terrific mike for studio recording. If you're looking for an inexpensive quality studio microphone, this is well worth your consideration. Read more 101 people found this helpful Helpful Report abuse John & Michelle5.0 out of 5 stars Video shows Installation and Comparison Reviewed in the United States on October 19, 2014Verified Purchase The media could not be loaded.  This video shows sound and quality at different settings as well as setting up tips. Settings used on microphone switches are the -10 switch and the flat line. Microphone properties volume set at 15 (on computer). It setup thru windows by plugging in the usb and windows added its own driver (same on both windows 7 and 8 computers I installed it to)It also set as a speaker so I had to switch after driver install to my default speaker.To install the stand remove ring from microphone put thru loop of stand and screw on ring clamping it in place. I started to cross thread the ring but when I flipped it, it threaded perfectly, so check this when installing to stand. The program used to record the video was  Photo and Video Pro Suite X5 . Read more 295 people found this helpful Helpful Report abuse ED5.0 out of 5 stars It's awesome. I used the included stand for years Reviewed in the United States on December 16, 2017Verified Purchase I've been using this for many years now since I bought it. Figured it's time for a quick review as I have filled out others recently.It's awesome. I used the included stand for years. but recently have switched to a mounted boom. The extremely long USB cable has been awesome to to use not only for the mic but also for charging various devices over the years.Note that it does pick up the faintest of noises, like my 1 year old talking up a storm downstairs and in the kitchen pretty far away the point I can barely hear him. In return, it does pick up whispers extremely well.Some tips:- Be sure to tune the buttons accordingly (keep the bass flat for podcasts and voice overs, as you want the bass in your voice).- Keep the pop filter (http://amzn.to/2yIhmXz) at least 6" away from the mic.- It does pick up too much ambient noises, even though the sound is not directed at the front of the mic.I'm using it with this microphone stand: http://amzn.to/2AVEJTuAnd this pop filter: http://amzn.to/2yIhmXz Read more 11 people found this helpful Helpful Report abuse Highly Recommend5.0 out of 5 stars Top Tier Consumer Microphone Reviewed in the United States on March 11, 2022Verified Purchase If you're looking for a reliable, quality mic for non-professional use, I strongly recommend this.I've had this mic for 7 years and it still performs great. Has a great pickup range so much so that it's remained effective even though I've mounted it to an arm and it sits BEHIND my monitor almost 3' away.Highly Recommend.One side note, I've attempt putting multiple foam pop filter covers over the mic itself and this has always resulted in, what others have described as, a "tapping noise" on their end. It's completely inaudible to you the user unless you listen to your own output but it'll drive your friends insane. Not sure what causes this but there it is. Read more Helpful Report abuse Ben5.0 out of 5 stars 5 YEAR REVIEW Reviewed in the United States on December 9, 2020Verified Purchase Ive been using this mic for over 5 years now. FIVE YEARS and it still sounds great. I use it for live streaming and just talking to friends and it’s got some of the best sound quality, especially in this price range. While this mic sounds great in discord with just a noise gate and volume control, this mic really shines when you get it into a software like OBS that has built in features like a compressor. Very very very highly recommend. Read more 3 people found this helpful Helpful Report abuse Choxie5.0 out of 5 stars 6 Years and Counting Reviewed in the United States on October 13, 2020Verified Purchase Can I just say I had this for 6 years, and it's still going strong. Use it for streaming, and talking to friends on discord and it's been a little beast ever since I bought it. I've tried to move onto a few mics in between to see if it's an "Upgrade" But those all failed me, including the Blue Yeti.Although this mic went up around 50% in price since I bought mine, I still highly recommend it! Read more 3 people found this helpful Helpful Report abuse Karl4.0 out of 5 stars Best Entry level Mic for its time. Reviewed in the United States on May 3, 2020Verified Purchase Plenty of other reviews talk about the audio quality of it so I won't cover that.What does need to be covered is the build quality itself. Mic is covered in a soft touch coating. These coatings are notorious for degrading over time and becoming a gross sticky mess. This mic is no exception. I've owned it since 2013 and not too long ago dipped the plastic shell in alchohol to break down said coating. The threads on the usb connection point can also be stripped if not careful. Read more 3 people found this helpful Helpful Report abuse See all reviews Top reviews from other countries LJ3.0 out of 5 stars Tried moving the mic further away from my mouth where I was a few feet away which just about made it sound OK and then it sounde Reviewed in the United Kingdom on April 27, 2017Verified Purchase I bought this mic for singing after reading reviews that it was "great for singing" and did the job well. I tried it for a couple of months, fiddled about with the settings, volume, etc. Tried also adjusting the settings on audacity (the recording software I use) but I still found that if I sang loud on some notes that the voice would clip (sounds nasty). Tried moving the mic further away from my mouth where I was a few feet away which just about made it sound OK and then it sounded like I was in a huge room (or too far from the mic - even increasing the volume of the mic didn't help). I looked up every way to fix the clipping issue and in the end the solution was to buy a proper microphone, which I did. I found that you can buy a USB cable that hooks up to normal microphones and connects to your laptop, so I bought a mic with a stand (under £30) and a USB cable (£10) and it works beautifully. I think if you just sing quiet songs, you're fine, or do podcasts but if you plan on singing anything with 'umph' think again. For the price, I was expecting better to be honest. Read more 6 people found this helpful Report abuse WildPortraitArtist3.0 out of 5 stars Very tinny sound... but it'll do for now. Reviewed in the United Kingdom on July 28, 2017Verified Purchase I run a youtube channel and needed a new mic for voicing over art tutorials. Compared to the Samson Go Mic that I was using before this, this mic has very tinny sound. The Go Mic has much richer sound. However I am glad to finally be rid of that tiny microphone because it picks up background noise so easily and won't fit on normal mic arms or shock mounts. The U37 will have to do for now and will hopefully tide me over until I can upgrade to a Rode eventually. But don't expect amazing sound quality with this mic, because it isn't there. Read more 2 people found this helpful Report abuse Julius3.0 out of 5 stars Sound quality is average Reviewed in the United Kingdom on January 31, 2018Verified Purchase I bought it for Youtube video making, however it does not suite my purpose at all. The quality is quite bad, it may not be bad product in overall since it is very good at catching sound from far away and I can speak on Skype even when I am being in a different room if I am loud enough and doors are open, but it is bad in terms of sound quality which I would prefer much more over the sensitivity when in the distance. So if you look for quality sound it is not the product to buy, if you look for sensitive microphone to use for sound recording in your classes or speaking through Skype in a distance it should be good enough. Read more Report abuse Anthony Williams5.0 out of 5 stars Hands down excellent value Reviewed in the United Kingdom on November 21, 2015Verified Purchase You wont find a cheaper more reliable USB Condenser, sound is crisp I absolutely love it, to think I was gonna pay £100+ for others that I was looking at. Took me hours of research before going for this one as amazon did not disappoint, plus if it doesn't work for you amazon offer no hassle returns. So this is one I would recommend for the beginner Read more 2 people found this helpful Report abuse Amazon Customer5.0 out of 5 stars I'm a radio person and a musician so I was hoping to use it for both recording my voice and my guitar and the quality of recordi Reviewed in the United Kingdom on May 5, 2016Verified Purchase Bought it on Wednesday, said it would arrive on Friday, came on Thursday. Points for Delivery.I'm a radio person and a musician so I was hoping to use it for both recording my voice and my guitar and the quality of recording on both is brilliant! The volume you can get is great and it picks up sounds really well (it worked when I tried recording from a few feet away and it still was pretty good). it has a really simple setup too so I got it going in no time.10/10 would buy again Read more 2 people found this helpful Report abuse See all reviews

Please try again later.Wayfinder5.0 out of 5 stars The only recording mike you'll need Reviewed in the United States on December 3, 2014Verified Purchase At first I was going to give this mike 4 stars because I'm a perfectionist and I've seen better studio mikes. But those studio mikes were expensive; this one is under $50. Therefore, 5 stars. Here's why:PROS:* Good quality recording with variable settings on the mike itself* Very easy to install. No driver software-- just plug it in and it works* Responsive cyan LED to help indicate power / recording level* Excellent size. When set on a table it's at just about the perfect height for recording* Surprisingly good sound quality, especially for a mike this light-weight and low-priced* Neat little table tripod stand, easy to set up and use* Comes with generous-length cableCONS:None really. Terrific little mike. These are more "be aware of these things when recording":* This is (as advertised) a studio mike. It is really, really, really sensitive and will pick up all sounds in the room-- including computer fans and a small 10" room fan I had set on low about 6 feet away. Such noise of course can be easily overcome in post-processing using a program such as Audacity (available free on the Net) or other music processing software.* That said, it has a "bass switch" that provides reduction of background noise by reducing mike sensitivity for some sound levels.* That said... the bass switch also alters the overall quality of recording sound. This can also be adjusted via post-processing.* THAT said... it's best to record in an enclosed room using a tablet or laptop with as little fan sound as possible, because this WILL pick up all sound in the room. It's meant to do so to provide distortion-free recording.For best recording I use this with my Windows tablet (zero fan noise, easy portability and setup). The result is a very effective "recording studio" which does a good job for not a lotta cash. Quality Windows tablets today can be purchased for around $200. So that along with this mike and free downloaded software provides a good recording environment that will suit the needs of many users. And of course it functions perfectly as a high-quality computer mike for Skype or other chat purposes.WHAT TO EXPECT:A good-quality voice and instrument recording mike. Solo voice/guitar? Yes. Computer voice mike? Yes but it will pick up background noise. Group mike? Yes, it's a studio mike; it picks up sound well.WHAT NOT TO EXPECT:Don't expect $300 + $20 wind screen sound recording from this. It has very good sound recording, but there are better mikes on the market if your budget allows. However if you're on a limited budget and want GOOD results and would like a USB mike that plugs right into your computer, I don't believe this can be beat. I've purchased several microphones and this has as good a quality sound recording as any mike I have purchased.This isn't a "band" mike. This is for use in "studio conditions" (ie, in a closed environment without background noise) directly plugged into your computer's USB port. Used as an outdoor mike at a concert or such... well I haven't tried that yet. Typically studio mikes are not good for such. Used in live performance: no. The background noise pickup and feedback potential would be immense.SOLO STUDIO RECORDING:Because it does pick up external noise you can play it with an acoustic instrument without miking the instrument separately; it will pick up about the same quality and positioning as the human ear. Interestingly this mike seems to work better from 12 inches than the standard 2 to 4 inches that most recording mikes prefer. I got excellent results when recording at 12". At 2" from the mouth the sound is still excellent but one gets the feeling of "really not necessary and is actually too much". 12" or even further seems perfect, which is great news for solo acoustic guitar performers.This mike would work equally well running an electric guitar through an amp and setting the amp to the side. The mike has such faithful reproduction of sound it should lose little or nothing in the distance translation.In short, a terrific mike for studio recording. If you're looking for an inexpensive quality studio microphone, this is well worth your consideration. But those studio mikes were expensive; this one is under $50. Therefore, 5 stars. Here's why:PROS:* Good quality recording with variable settings on the mike itself* Very easy to install. No driver software-- just plug it in and it works* Responsive cyan LED to help indicate power / recording level* Excellent size. When set on a table it's at just about the perfect height for recording* Surprisingly good sound quality, especially for a mike this light-weight and low-priced* Neat little table tripod stand, easy to set up and use* Comes with generous-length cableCONS:None really. Terrific little mike. These are more "be aware of these things when recording":* This is (as advertised) a studio mike. It is really, really, really sensitive and will pick up all sounds in the room-- including computer fans and a small 10" room fan I had set on low about 6 feet away. Such noise of course can be easily overcome in post-processing using a program such as Audacity (available free on the Net) or other music processing software.* That said, it has a "bass switch" that provides reduction of background noise by reducing mike sensitivity for some sound levels.* That said... the bass switch also alters the overall quality of recording sound. This can also be adjusted via post-processing.* THAT said... it's best to record in an enclosed room using a tablet or laptop with as little fan sound as possible, because this WILL pick up all sound in the room. It's meant to do so to provide distortion-free recording.For best recording I use this with my Windows tablet (zero fan noise, easy portability and setup). The result is a very effective "recording studio" which does a good job for not a lotta cash. Quality Windows tablets today can be purchased for around $200. So that along with this mike and free downloaded software provides a good recording environment that will suit the needs of many users. And of course it functions perfectly as a high-quality computer mike for Skype or other chat purposes.WHAT TO EXPECT:A good-quality voice and instrument recording mike. Solo voice/guitar? Yes. Computer voice mike? Yes but it will pick up background noise. Group mike? Yes, it's a studio mike; it picks up sound well.WHAT NOT TO EXPECT:Don't expect $300 + $20 wind screen sound recording from this. It has very good sound recording, but there are better mikes on the market if your budget allows. However if you're on a limited budget and want GOOD results and would like a USB mike that plugs right into your computer, I don't believe this can be beat. I've purchased several microphones and this has as good a quality sound recording as any mike I have purchased.This isn't a "band" mike. This is for use in "studio conditions" (ie, in a closed environment without background noise) directly plugged into your computer's USB port. Used as an outdoor mike at a concert or such... well I haven't tried that yet. Typically studio mikes are not good for such. Used in live performance: no. The background noise pickup and feedback potential would be immense.SOLO STUDIO RECORDING:Because it does pick up external noise you can play it with an acoustic instrument without miking the instrument separately; it will pick up about the same quality and positioning as the human ear. Interestingly this mike seems to work better from 12 inches than the standard 2 to 4 inches that most recording mikes prefer. I got excellent results when recording at 12". At 2" from the mouth the sound is still excellent but one gets the feeling of "really not necessary and is actually too much". 12" or even further seems perfect, which is great news for solo acoustic guitar performers.This mike would work equally well running an electric guitar through an amp and setting the amp to the side. The mike has such faithful reproduction of sound it should lose little or nothing in the distance translation.In short, a terrific mike for studio recording. If you're looking for an inexpensive quality studio microphone, this is well worth your consideration. Wayfinder5.0 out of 5 stars The only recording mike you'll need Reviewed in the United States on December 3, 2014Verified Purchase At first I was going to give this mike 4 stars because I'm a perfectionist and I've seen better studio mikes. But those studio mikes were expensive; this one is under $50. Therefore, 5 stars. Here's why:PROS:* Good quality recording with variable settings on the mike itself* Very easy to install. No driver software-- just plug it in and it works* Responsive cyan LED to help indicate power / recording level* Excellent size. When set on a table it's at just about the perfect height for recording* Surprisingly good sound quality, especially for a mike this light-weight and low-priced* Neat little table tripod stand, easy to set up and use* Comes with generous-length cableCONS:None really. Terrific little mike. These are more "be aware of these things when recording":* This is (as advertised) a studio mike. It is really, really, really sensitive and will pick up all sounds in the room-- including computer fans and a small 10" room fan I had set on low about 6 feet away. Such noise of course can be easily overcome in post-processing using a program such as Audacity (available free on the Net) or other music processing software.* That said, it has a "bass switch" that provides reduction of background noise by reducing mike sensitivity for some sound levels.* That said... the bass switch also alters the overall quality of recording sound. This can also be adjusted via post-processing.* THAT said... it's best to record in an enclosed room using a tablet or laptop with as little fan sound as possible, because this WILL pick up all sound in the room. It's meant to do so to provide distortion-free recording.For best recording I use this with my Windows tablet (zero fan noise, easy portability and setup). The result is a very effective "recording studio" which does a good job for not a lotta cash. Quality Windows tablets today can be purchased for around $200. So that along with this mike and free downloaded software provides a good recording environment that will suit the needs of many users. And of course it functions perfectly as a high-quality computer mike for Skype or other chat purposes.WHAT TO EXPECT:A good-quality voice and instrument recording mike. Solo voice/guitar? Yes. Computer voice mike? Yes but it will pick up background noise. Group mike? Yes, it's a studio mike; it picks up sound well.WHAT NOT TO EXPECT:Don't expect $300 + $20 wind screen sound recording from this. It has very good sound recording, but there are better mikes on the market if your budget allows. However if you're on a limited budget and want GOOD results and would like a USB mike that plugs right into your computer, I don't believe this can be beat. I've purchased several microphones and this has as good a quality sound recording as any mike I have purchased.This isn't a "band" mike. This is for use in "studio conditions" (ie, in a closed environment without background noise) directly plugged into your computer's USB port. Used as an outdoor mike at a concert or such... well I haven't tried that yet. Typically studio mikes are not good for such. Used in live performance: no. The background noise pickup and feedback potential would be immense.SOLO STUDIO RECORDING:Because it does pick up external noise you can play it with an acoustic instrument without miking the instrument separately; it will pick up about the same quality and positioning as the human ear. Interestingly this mike seems to work better from 12 inches than the standard 2 to 4 inches that most recording mikes prefer. I got excellent results when recording at 12". At 2" from the mouth the sound is still excellent but one gets the feeling of "really not necessary and is actually too much". 12" or even further seems perfect, which is great news for solo acoustic guitar performers.This mike would work equally well running an electric guitar through an amp and setting the amp to the side. The mike has such faithful reproduction of sound it should lose little or nothing in the distance translation.In short, a terrific mike for studio recording. If you're looking for an inexpensive quality studio microphone, this is well worth your consideration. When set on a table it's at just about the perfect height for recording* Surprisingly good sound quality, especially for a mike this light-weight and low-priced* Neat little table tripod stand, easy to set up and use* Comes with generous-length cableCONS:None really.  Terrific little mike.  These are more "be aware of these things when recording":* This is (as advertised) a studio mike.  It is really, really, really sensitive and will pick up all sounds in the room-- including computer fans and a small 10" room fan I had set on low about 6 feet away.  Such noise of course can be easily overcome in post-processing using a program such as Audacity (available free on the Net) or other music processing software.* That said, it has a "bass switch" that provides reduction of  background noise by reducing mike sensitivity for some sound levels.* That said... the bass switch also alters the overall quality of recording sound.  This can also be adjusted via post-processing.* THAT said... it's best to record in an enclosed room using a tablet or laptop with as little fan sound as possible, because this WILL pick up all sound in the room.  It's meant to do so to provide distortion-free recording.For best recording I use this with my Windows tablet (zero fan noise, easy portability and setup).  The result is a very effective "recording studio" which does a good job for not a lotta cash.  Quality Windows tablets today can be purchased for around $200.  So that along with this mike and free downloaded software provides a good recording environment that will suit the needs of many users.  And of course it functions perfectly as a high-quality computer mike for Skype or other chat purposes.WHAT TO EXPECT:A good-quality voice and instrument recording mike.  Solo voice/guitar?  Yes.  Computer voice mike?  Yes but it will pick up background noise.  Group mike?  Yes, it's a studio mike; it picks up sound well.WHAT NOT TO EXPECT:Don't expect $300 + $20 wind screen sound recording from this.  It has very good sound recording, but there are better mikes on the market if your budget allows.  However if you're on a limited budget and want GOOD results and would like a USB mike that plugs right into your computer, I don't believe this can be beat.  I've purchased several microphones and this has as good a quality sound recording as any mike I have purchased.This isn't a "band" mike.  This is for use in "studio conditions" (ie, in a closed environment without background noise) directly plugged into your computer's USB port.  Used as an outdoor mike at a concert or such... well I haven't tried that yet.  Typically studio mikes are not good for such.  Used in live performance:  no.  The background noise pickup and feedback potential would be immense.SOLO STUDIO RECORDING:Because it does pick up external noise you can play it with an acoustic instrument without miking the instrument separately; it will pick up about the same quality and positioning as the human ear.  Interestingly this mike seems to work better from 12 inches than the standard 2 to 4 inches that most recording mikes prefer.  I got excellent results when recording at 12".  At 2" from the mouth the sound is still excellent but one gets the feeling of "really not necessary and is actually too much".  12" or even further seems perfect, which is great news for solo acoustic guitar performers.This mike would work equally well running an electric guitar through an amp and setting the amp to the side.  The mike has such faithful reproduction of sound it should lose little or nothing in the distance translation.In short, a terrific mike for studio recording.  If you're looking for an inexpensive quality studio microphone, this is well worth your consideration.

Top reviews from other countries LJ3.0 out of 5 stars Tried moving the mic further away from my mouth where I was a few feet away which just about made it sound OK and then it sounde Reviewed in the United Kingdom on April 27, 2017Verified Purchase I bought this mic for singing after reading reviews that it was "great for singing" and did the job well. I tried it for a couple of months, fiddled about with the settings, volume, etc. Tried also adjusting the settings on audacity (the recording software I use) but I still found that if I sang loud on some notes that the voice would clip (sounds nasty). Tried moving the mic further away from my mouth where I was a few feet away which just about made it sound OK and then it sounded like I was in a huge room (or too far from the mic - even increasing the volume of the mic didn't help). I looked up every way to fix the clipping issue and in the end the solution was to buy a proper microphone, which I did. I found that you can buy a USB cable that hooks up to normal microphones and connects to your laptop, so I bought a mic with a stand (under £30) and a USB cable (£10) and it works beautifully. I think if you just sing quiet songs, you're fine, or do podcasts but if you plan on singing anything with 'umph' think again. For the price, I was expecting better to be honest.
